<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   UK Denies Report on Talks in North on Arming Azerbaijan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2401205394 Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY in English 1841 GMT 
24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2401205394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] London, Jan 24 (CNA)--Britain's Foreign Office 
described as "rumours" late Monday [24 January] a front page 
article by a British daily, suggesting that the Turkish-occupied 
areas in Cyprus were used as negotiating ground for the supply 
of military aid to Azerbaijan. 
  "THE INDEPENDENT" wrote Monday that the British Government 
had given "tacit support to an illegal scheme to supply 
Azerbaijan with military backing in its war with Armenia." 
  The military backing, according to the newspaper, included 
both the supply of arms and "a large number of mercenaries." 
  Moreover, "THE INDEPENDENT" wrote that the negotiating 
sides' 
representatives were based in Cyprus' Turkish-occupied areas 
"where it is not illegal to trade in arms to Azerbaijan." 
  The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared independence in 
1983. The illegal entity is recognised only by Turkey, which 
occupies 37 percent of the island's territory since 1974. 
  The transactions were confirmed by Lord Erskine of Rerrick, 
68, who, according to the daily, lives in these areas but is to 
return to the U.K. within a month. 
  Lord Erskine confirmed to the daily that the negotiations 
had 
taken place between Azeri authorities and a consortium for which 
he is acting as consultant. 

</TEXT>

