<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Opposes British Army Exercises in East </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2501092694 Hamburg DER SPIEGEL in German 24 Jan 94 p 16 </F>
<F P=103> AU2501092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DER SPIEGEL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Exercises in the East?"] </F>
  [Text] A controversy on security policy has broken out 
between the governments in Bonn and London. Britain would like 
to transfer several units of its Rhine Army to eastern Germany 
for exercises. Last week, the Foreign Ministry categorically 
rejected Britain's request. The background lies in disputes 
about the Two-Plus-Four Agreement on German unity. Under that 
agreement, all of Germany will be counted as NATO area once the 
Russians have pulled out. However, the agreement stipulates that 
"foreign armed forces" would "neither be deployed in nor 
transferred to" the former GDR. In 1990, the allies agreed with 
the two German states to leave it to the united Germans to 
interpret the term "transfer." The British request has 
maneuvered Bonn into a dilemma. The Russian Government might 
regard the authorization of Rhine Army exercises in eastern 
Germany as an affront and slow down the faster-than-planned 
troop withdrawal. Yet, Bonn does not want to put off the 
British either, which is why the Federal Government is playing 
for time at the moment. 

</TEXT>

