<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   CDU Reelects Kohl Bundestag Candidate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401143294 Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG in German 23 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg WELT AM SONNTAG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "lrs": "69 of 72 Votes for Candidate Kohl"] </F>
  [Text] Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl, of the Christian 
Democratic Union [CDU], was reelected as a candidate to the 
Bundestag for his party in the Ludwigshafen constituency late on 
Friday [21 January] night. 
  Kohl, who is running for Ludwigshafen the sixth time, 
received 69 of the 72 valid votes in the meeting of the 
constituency delegates. Three delegates voted against the CDU 
federal chairman. 
  Kohl's Social Democratic Party [SPD] opponent in the 
constituency is Doris Barnett (40), head of the social 
administrative office in Ludwigshafen, who was nominated in late 
November 1993. In his nomination address to an audience of 300, 
Kohl strongly warned against slackening determination to 
struggle for European unification. Germans would have "to pay 
bitterly" if they wanted to opt out of the unification process. 
  Kohl called for a rethinking process, and said people should 
not expect the level of benefits and rights to continue to rise 
forever. To maintain international competitive strength, 
enterprises in Germany must be made more flexible. The current 
round of wage talks offers an opportunity for this, as can be 
seen by the agreement achieved in the chemical industry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

