<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciampi Rejects Interior Minister's Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101195494 Paris AFP in English 1936 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Rome, Jan 21 (AFP) -- Italian Interior Minister 
Nicola Mancino tendered his resignation Friday [21 January] over 
a scandal involving secret service funds but saw the offer 
rejected by Prime Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, officials said. 
  Mancino offered to quit saying that Rome prosecutors had 
gathered documents which could lead to his being investigated in 
connection with the Sisde (intelligence service) affair 
involving corruption in the funding of the secret services. 
  The documents in question had been sent to the three 
investigating judges who could launch legal proceedings against 
him, officials said. 
  But Ciampi said in a statement that he had "full confidence" 
in Mancino, adding that the transfer of documents for 
consideration by the judges "is an obligatory measure, which 
does not constitute a formal charge." 
  Mancino was implicated in the Sisde affair along with three 
former interior ministers, including current Italian President 
Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, by former members of the secret services. 

</TEXT>

