<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Announces Cuts in Eurofighter 2000 Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2101195694 Paris AFP in English 1917 GMT 21 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2101195694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Madrid, Jan 21 (AFP) -- Britain, Germany, Italy and 
Spain agreed here Friday [21 January] to cut the costs of their 
jointly-developed Eurofighter project by 30 percent, the Spanish 
defence ministry said. 
  The heads of the respective air forces which signed the 
accord at the Toreejon air force base near here confirmed their 
support for talks currently under way with the manufacturers to 
reduce the price of each aircraft. 
  The Eurofighter project, a lighter version of the original 
European Combat Aircraft, was launched in December 1992 in the 
wake of defence budget cuts and changing requirements after the 
end of the Cold War. 
  The aircraft is being funded 37.5 percent by Britain, 3O 
percent by Germany, 19.5 percent by Italy and 13 percent by 
Spain. 

</TEXT>

