<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demirel Hosts Dinner for Weizman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2401204794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 2000 
GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2401204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] President Suleyman Demirel has declared that Turkey 
would like the countries in the Middle East to expend their 
energy and resources for the economic development of their 
peoples and to solve their problems through constructive 
dialogue. 
  Demirel hosted a dinner in honor of Israeli President Ever 
Weizman. In a dinner toast, Demirel welcomed the beginning of 
the Middle East peace process. He explained that the courageous 
steps taken by Israel and the Palestinians last year enabled 
Turkey to transport its efforts for cooperation and peace 
southward. The existing desire to perpetuate peace will be 
reflected widely and positively in the world, Demirel stressed. 
  Recalling that the relations between the Turkish and Jewish 
people began a long time ago, Demirel noted that Turkish 
citizens of Jewish origin contribute significantly to the 
country and its cultural heritage. 
  In his speech, Weizman said that he came to Turkey, knowing 
that it is a country with an influential role in the future 
course of the Middle East. Underlining that Turkey has always 
contributed to peace, Weizman remarked: The leaders and people 
of the Middle East should embrace Kemal Ataturk's motto of peace 
at home and peace in the world. 
  There are many factors that connect the two nations and the 
two countries, Weizman recounted, adding that Israel will never 
forget that the Jews were accepted by the Ottoman Empire when 
they were expelled from various European countries some 500 
years ago. Weizman pointed out that thousands of Arabs and Jews 
were killed in the wars waged before it was understood that 
Israel's existence in the region is a living reality. He added 
that the agreement with the Palestinians constitutes the 
beginning of a change in the region. 

</TEXT>

