<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christopher, Juppe Comment on NATO Decision on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401192194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1823 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2401192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Paris, Jan 24 (TANJUG) -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher said in Paris on Monday [24 January] that the 
United States was prepared to engage in the implementation of 
NATO's decision to launch air strikes against Bosnian Serbs if 
such an action was demanded by military commanders on the ground. 
  French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said after meeting 
Christopher it was important to implement NATO decisions when 
Tuzla and Srebrenica were concerned. 
  It is difficult to conclude from the two statements whether 
Paris and Washington had agreed over what Washington described 
as the insufficiently clarified diplomatic initiative launched 
by Paris to help resolve the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  At the recent NATO summit in Brussels, France was the 
staunchest advocator of the use of air power against Bosnian 
Serbs for their alleged refusal to reopen the local airport in 
Tuzla, the Moslem enclave in northeastern Bosnia, and allow the 
replacement of Canadian U.N. troops in another Moslem enclave, 
Srebrenica in eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Bosnian Serbs have reached agreement with the U.N. Bosnia 
command to allow Dutch peacekeepers to replace the Canadians in 
Srebrenica in early February, but rejected to reopen the airport 
in Tuzla before a general peace accord has been signed, fearing 
that the facility may be used for arms shipment to Bosnian 
Moslems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

