<H3> <TI>   Meets With Balladur, Mitterrand </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2401214294 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 
1900 GMT 24 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2401214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Diplomats are desperately looking for a way out [on 
Bosnia], desperately, in the literal sense of the word. The 
American secretary of state, Warren Christopher, was in Paris 
today. Stephane Manier reports: 
  [Manier] Warren Christopher was not expecting this. He was 
not expecting the French to bring up for discussion the Bosnian 
issue with so much insistence, including with President 
Mitterrand this evening. It was also the case one hour earlier 
with Prime Minister Edouard Balladur. The French repeated what 
Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said this morning. 
  [Begin Juppe recording] However precious humanitarian aid 
may 
be, it is not sufficient to settle the problem, of course. A 
political settlement is the only way out. [end recording] 
  It is obvious that the French did not want the Americans to 
say only that they were ready to bomb Serbian artillery at any 
time, but that they would become involved on the ground. 
However, the Americans have not changed their position since 
the NATO summit in Brussels. 
  [Begin Christopher recording in English with superimposed 
French translation] The United States is not ready to have 
ground troops in Bosnia to impose a solution in this conflict. 
[end recording] 
  So the Americans have appeared really annoyed by the French 
insistence, and Christopher's entourage speculated this evening: 
aren't the French trying to make us take the blame for their 
future withdrawal next spring? It is indeed difficult for the 
Western side to speak with one voice. As for him, Warren 
Christopher preferred to get into his limousine quickly. 

</TEXT>

