<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Kooijmans Opposed to Departure of Owen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2401160394 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 22 Jan 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BR2401160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Kooijmans Seeks Change in EU </F>
Negotiator Owen's Mandate"] 
  [Text] After France, the Netherlands now also wants to hold 
emergency consultations by the European Union [EU] on the 
situation in Bosnia and the mandate of the British negotiator, 
Lord Owen. According to Foreign Minister Kooijmans, it is unfair 
that the EU negotiator is now being used as the scapegoat for 
the international failure to achieve a peace settlement in the 
former Yugoslavia. 
  Kooijmans affirmed on Friday [21 January] that the action 
plan has failed. The member states must, therefore, ask 
themselves whether or not to further pursue the present path. 
The EU should not be considering whether or not to send Lord 
Owen home, but rather a change in his mandate. As to the nature 
of the change he envisages, he is not prepared to say at 
present. The motion by the European Parliament, which demanded 
Lord Owen's departure, was received poorly in The Hague on 
Friday. At a press conference in The Hague, UN Secretary 
General Butrus-Ghali praised the wonderful work by Owen and 
Stoltenberg. He said he would continue to support them as their 
work required patience, political will, and stamina. 
  The four largest groups in the Second Chamber see the 
replacement of Owen as being of little value, as it does not 
bring an end to the conflict any nearer. They agree with 
Kooijmans that the real problem is not Owen, but the impotence 
of the international community. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

