<H3> <TI>   Loeschnak Comments on Letter-Bomb Investigations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2401161494 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 24 Jan 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> AU2401161494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "stui": "Loeschnak: Right-Wing Extremist </F>
Background to Letter Bombs Unpleasant for Haider"] 
  [Excerpt] Vienna -- Two of the four suspects in the 
letter-bomb affair who are still in prison "were involved in the 
attacks in one way or another," Interior Minister Franz 
Loeschnak stated on Sunday [23 January] during the "Meet the 
Press" program. Loeschnak hopes that the judiciary will be able 
to present an "intermediate result" for a bill of indictment by 
the end of the month. The interior minister considers it a 
proven fact that the attacks were carried out by "perpetrators 
completely familiar with the right-wing scene in Austria, and 
clearly xenophobic." 
  He believes that the suggestion by Joerg Haider, chairman of 
the Freedom Party of Austria [FPOe], that by investigating the 
right-wing scene the authorities were following a "dead-end 
road," can only be explained by the fact that this is 
"unpleasant" for Haider. After all, Horst Jakob Rosenkranz, the 
husband of Lower Austrian FPOe deputy Barbara Rosenkranz, "was 
clearly recognizable" on a video together with one of the 
suspects. 
  This statement led to furious protests among the FPOe. 
Haider described Loeschnak's attacks as "unjustified." He 
stresed that, together with the ORF, Loeschnak is attempting to 
disparage the whole FPOe. 
  Loeschnak admitted that government forces were "surprised" 
at 
the strength of the right-wing extremist scene. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

