<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Longuet Assures `Dragons' About Beijing Deal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2501090994 Paris LE FIGARO (LE FIG-ECO supplement) in 
French 22-23 Jan 94 p I </F>

<F P=103> BR2501090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE FIGARO (LE FIG-ECO supplement) </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Arnaud Rodier: "Armament -- France Reassures </F>
`Dragons'"] 
  [Text] It is no accident that [Foreign Trade Minister] 
Gerard Longuet -- intent on reaffirming that France does not 
intend to burn all bridges with Taiwan -- chose to make this 
statement in Singapore. 
  Industry and External Trade Minister Gerard Longuet wants 
everybody to be happy. He reaffirmed yesterday in Singapore 
that, on 12 January, France did not undertake to cease selling 
weapons to Taiwan altogether, but only those weapons "deemed 
offensive for mainland China" or "likely to threaten its 
integrity or its security." 
  This is a way for Mr. Longuet to expand on statements made 
by 
Defense Minister Francois Leotard, who insisted last week on the 
fact that Paris reserved the right to continue selling 
"nonoffensive" equipment to Taiwan. 
  However, choosing to do it from Singapore was no accident. 
  France, which will supply 60 Mirage 2000-5 fighter aircraft 
and their weaponry to Taiwan, knows that it must give up hope of 
selling it three assault submarines worth 20 billion francs. 
<H5>  Making Up For Lost Time </H5>
  However, France has not given up its intention of selling 
assault armored vehicles as well as Roland missiles, since such 
equipment can very well be considered as defensive weapons. And 
above all, France does not want to lose other customers in the 
region, including Singapore. 
  "The agreement signed with Beijing is likely to open markets 
which were hitherto closed to France, but it also creates a risk 
of destabilization for noncommunist countries, including 
Southeast Asia's `dragons,'" says a weapons manufacturer. 
  This analysis applies not only to the defense industry, but 
also to civilian sectors. And, as reaffirmed yesterday by 
Gerard Longuet, France wishes to position itself in Singapore so 
as to be better placed in Malaysia, India, and Vietnam. 
  France did not prove active enough in this region. It needs 
to "make up for lost time," insists Mr. Longuet. 
  As for manufacturers, from Aerospatiale to Thomson to 
Alcatel-Alsthom, if the government works toward smoothing things 
out, so much the better. Improved relations between Paris and 
Beijing are expected to help Airbus Industries sell its aircraft 
in China. However, this does not justify ignoring other 
countries, which would immediately turn to the United States 
anyway. 
<H5>  Minister Seeks To Reassure </H5>
  Singapore is one of them. Its influence in the region is 
substantial. Accordingly, Gerard Longuet waxes reassuringly 
toward those who fear France might focus on China to the 
detriment of everyone else. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-58990 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu016_i_94003" </HT>


