<H3> <TI>   Delors Reports on Meeting With Turkey's Ciller </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1401093594 Brussels EUROPE in English 13 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1401093594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels EUROPE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Delors Meets Turkish Prime </F>
Minister"; as released by Brussels TEXTLINE database] 
  [Text] "We discussed all problems. We did not avoid any of 
the difficult issues," said Jacques Delors at the conclusion of 
his meeting on Tuesday [11 January] with Turkish Prime Minister 
Mrs. Tansu Ciller. The president of the Commission mentioned 
the following: 

  -  Customs union. Mrs. Ciller outlined her 
country's efforts to complete union by the deadline that has 
been fixed (1995); 
  -  The EC/Turkey financial protocol, which is 
still deadlocked. "I have an idea about how to break the 
deadlock," said Mr. Delors; 
  -  Cyprus. "I think that if we find a 
solution for Cyprus, many of the obstacles now in our path will 
be removed, to Turkey's advantage," commented Mr. Delors. He 
added that the EC observer to the UN negotiations will only have 
the task of "keeping us updated on the negotiations"; 
  -  The 
Kurdish problem. "The Prime Minister explained her analysis of 
the situation and the efforts she is making to make the country 
more democratic and decentralize decisions. She hopes to 
promote a more active democracy enabling all citizens to 
participate in public affairs," said the president; 
  -  Former USSR. 
The southernmost countries of the former USSR were discussed. 
Mr. Delors commented: "It was very interesting for us to 
benefit from the experience of Turkey, which provides 
considerable aid for these countries." Mrs. Ciller then took 
part in an enlarged meeting with her minister of foreign 
affairs, Mr. Hikmet Cetin, and European Commissioners Sir Leon 
Brittan and Hans van den Broek. 

</TEXT>

