<H3> <TI>   Russian Commander Provides Troop Withdrawal Details </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501151794 Hamburg DPA in German 1340 GMT 25 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2501151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin (DPA) -- The Western Group of Russian Forces 
has so far withdrawn 90 percent of its troops from eastern 
Germany. The withdrawal schedule for last year was therefore 
fully adhered to, Colonel General Matvey Burlakov, commander in 
chief [of the Western Group of Forces], told journalists in 
Berlin today. 
  The last soldier will return to Russia 31 August 1994 as 
planned. Official functions marking the farewell to the troops 
are to take place in the capital at the beginning of August. 
President Boris Yeltsin has promised to attend. 
  According to Burlakov, the remaining 68,000 personnel, 
including 32,000 servicemen and officers, as well as 17,500 
items of equipment, will be withdrawn this year. Not a single 
piece of ammunition will remain in Germany. 
  In contrast to the withdrawal of troops, only 65 percent of 
program for building apartments for the servicemen and their 
families returning home has been completed, Burlakov said, and 
40-45 percent of families are still without an apartment. 
  Another 25,000 apartments must be built this year with 
German 
funding and 22,000 with Russian funding. However, Burlakov 
doubts whether the program will be adhered to. Germany has 
promised to contribute 8 billion marks. 

</TEXT>

