<H3> <TI>   Bundeswehr Chief Calls For Participation in UN Missions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901185794 Hamburg DPA in German 1708 GMT 19 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1901185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg (DPA) -- Klaus Naumann, the general chief of 
staff of the Bundeswehr, spoke strongly in favor of changing the 
Constitution to enable the Bundeswehr to take part in all 
international UN missions. As a matter of principle, Germany 
should be in a position to fulfill its obligations as a UN 
member, or as a member of the Western European Union or NATO, he 
said. 
  "It is a matter of saying yes in principle, so that it is 
possible to say no in each individual case without raising 
issues of reliability," Naumann said today before the Hamburg 
Overseas Club. However, a military operation of this type must 
not always be the last resort: "It is by no means the case that 
we soldiers need such a mission for purposes of 
self-confirmation." 

</TEXT>

