<H3> <TI>   Russian Security Expert: Expansion Would Weaken NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2501120294 Hamburg DPA in German 1020 GMT 25 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2501120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Berlin (DPA) -- Russian security expert Sergey 
Karaganov has spoken in favor of a "very strong" NATO to deter 
the "worst militant elements" in Russia. At a security policy 
conference in Berlin today, Karaganov, deputy director of the 
Institute of European Affairs of the Russian Academy of 
Sciences, at the same time opposed the admission of East 
European countries into NATO. 
  Enlarging NATO by admitting the countries of East and 
Central 
Europe interested in joining the alliance would "water down" 
NATO's strength, Karaganov said. Russia's minimum security 
interest was not being excluded from new alliance structures, he 
said. 
  The Partnership for Peace offered by NATO to the former 
Warsaw Pact states opened up the prospect of an expansion of the 
Western defense alliance, said Walter B. Slocombe of the U.S. 
Defense Department. Failure of the reforms in Russia would also 
have destabilizing repercussions on Western countries, he said. 
[passage omitted] 

