<H3> <TI>   Institute Says Zhirinovskiy Will Deter Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701094894 Hamburg DPA in German 0702 GMT 17 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1701094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Munich (DPA) -- In the view of the Munich-based Ifo 
Institute for Economic Research, uncertainty about future 
political developments in Russia will lead to great caution on 
the part of potential Western investors and the International 
Monetary Fund (IMF) in the next two years as well. The Ifo 
Institute cites in particular Zhirinovskiy's success at the 
parliamentary elections in December 1993 and his goal to replace 
Boris Yeltsin as Russian president in 1996. The Russian reform 
and stabilization program adopted in the autumn of 1993 also 
contains problematic taxation plans. 
  In view of the massive tax evasion in Russia, it would be 
desirable to go back to administratively simpler taxes which are 
difficult to evade, the Ifo Institute writes. The institute 
also proposes property taxation. The Russian budget deficit for 
1993 will probably be 1.5 to 2 trillion rubles higher than 
planned. At the end of 1993 the government also approved a cash 
injection of 550 billion rubles for the arms industry and took 
emergency measures to alleviate the energy crisis in the CIS 
caused by the cold winter. 

</TEXT>

