<H3> <TI>   Protest Rally in Hesse Condemns Right-Wing Extremism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1601153194 Hamburg DPA in German 1335 GMT 15 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1601153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Giessen (DPA) -- Some 250 people joined a 
protest rally against the federal party congress of the National 
Democratic Party of Germany (NPD) in Ehringshausen in Hesse 
today. On banners, on leaflets, and in chants the demonstrators 
condemned right-wing extremism and xenophobia. 
  According to police information, the demonstration passed 
peacefully and without incident. It ended at midday. The party 
congress was protected by a large number of police. [passage 
omitted] 
  The NPD party congress, which was attended by about 200 
delegates, is due to end this evening. The police had also set 
up cordons in the surrounding area. According to the federal 
chairman of the NPD, Guenter Deckert, the party congress was to 
nominate among others candidates for European elections. 
According to estimates by the Federal Office for the Protection 
of the Constitution, which says the NPD shows unconstitutional 
tendencies, the party has about 5,000 members throughout Germany. 

</TEXT>

