<H3> <TI>   Officials Meet Hungarian Parliamentary Delegation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1401211394 Budapest MTI in English 1715 GMT 14 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1401211394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 14 January (MTI) -- Hungarian 
Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee delegates led by Chairman 
Laszlo Kovacs in Germany this week invited by the Bundestag, 
talked to Bundestag President Rita Sussmuth and senior Foreign 
and Defence Ministry officials. 
  The Hungarian deputies told their German hosts that although 
the Partnership for Peace scheme was less than what East Central 
Europe wanted, it was more than this region had ever got before. 
The scheme does not draw new dividing lines in Europe but 
promotes the region's rapproachement to NATO, at the same time 
not making Russia feel that NATO is forging an alliance against 
it. 
  Hungarian deputies asked Germany to help fill the Hungary-EC 
association agreement with genuine content, and promote 
Hungary's integration into the common European foreign and 
security policy. 
  German negotiators said that admitting European Free Trade 
Association [EFTA] countries was now on the agenda in the 
European Union, a process that should end by January 1995. Then 
a Union conference will review experiences of new members, 
admissions, and the association agreements. Talks with the 
Visegrad countries on full membership will not start before 
1997, Kovacs quoted his German partners as saying. 

</TEXT>

