<F P=101> Switzerland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qiao Shi To Visit European Nuclear Research Organization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2501104594 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1728 GMT 23 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BR2501104594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed Bn: "Official Visit by the President of the </F>
Chinese Parliament in Switzerland: Meeting with Stich and 
Cotti"; as released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Text] Bern 23 Jan -- Qiao Shi, PRC NPC [National People's 
Congress] president, began a four-day official visit in 
Switzerland on Sunday [23 January]. On Monday he will meet Otto 
Stich, president of the Confederation, and Flavio Cotti, chief 
of the Federal Department of Foreign Affairs. At the heart of 
the talks will be bilateral economic relations and the question 
of Tibet. Two associations have protested against the visit of 
the former head of secret police. 
  Qiao Shi was received at Kloten Airport by Ricardo Jagmetti, 
president of the State Council. Besides economic relations 
between the two countries, the question of Tibet will probably 
be tackled, as John Clerc, secretary general of the Federal 
Assembly, indicated. 
<H5>  CERN and Chillon Castle </H5>
  The president of the Chinese NPC will be welcomed on Monday 
by Federal Counselors Otto Stich and Flavio Cotti as well as by 
Gret Haller, president of the National Council. On Tuesday, Mr. 
Qiao will visit CERN [European Organization for Nuclear 
Research] in Geneva and Chillon Castle, both in the French part 
of Switzerland. He concludes his visit on Wednesday with a stop 
at the federal polytechnic school. 
  Mr. Qiao, 69, is considered the third most powerful man in 
the Beijing regime. A member of the Politbureau permanent 
committee, he is also a former head of the secret police. 
  The visit by the president of the Chinese NPC has already 
resulted in protests. The Swiss German central PEN-Club, which 
protested on Saturday, stated that Qiao Shi is one of the 
principal authorities responsible for the bloody human rights 
repressions in China during the last decade. 
  The central PEN-Club points to thousands of people, 
including 
many writers, who have been imprisoned in China without judicial 
procedure. 
  They add that economic interests do not justify inviting 
Qiao 
Shi to Switzerland. 
<H5>  Colonialist and Soldiers </H5>
  On Friday, the association "Tibetan Youth in Europe" had 
asked the Federal Council to discuss the violations of human 
rights in Tibet with Qiao Shi. Due to the colonization politics 
and to the reinforcement of the Chinese military presence, 6 
million Tibetans are now confronted with 7 million Chinese 
colonialists and soldiers, the association stated. 
  The last visit to Switzerland by a high level Chinese 
visitor 
was in January 1992, when State Council Premier Li Peng had a 
talk with Confederation President Rene Felber and with Public 
Economic Chief Jean-Pascal Delamuraz. During that meeting, some 
200 Tibetans and members of human rights organizations held a 
demonstration. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-59040 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu017__a94034" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-017 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Switzerland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Meet PRC's Qiao Shi 24 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2501162994 Bern ATSA/SDAA in French 1733 GMT 24 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2501162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bern ATSA/SDAA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed NI, SH: "The President of the Chinese </F>
Parliament Received in Bern; Human Rights on the Menu"; as 
released by Bern ATSA/SDAA database] 
  [Excerpts] Bern, 24 Jan (ATSA) -- Human rights dominated 
the conversations Qiao Shi, chairman of the Chinese National 
People's Congress, held in Bern on Monday [24 January]. Federal 
Councillor Flavio Cotti and National Council President Gret 
Haller expressed their concern about the human rights situation 
in China, particularly in Tibet. Confederation President Otto 
Stich promised China his country's support in case it seeks 
reintegration into GATT. 
  Mr. Cotti underlined that the human rights question 
particularly preoccupies Swiss public opinion. According to 
Franz Egle, his spokesman, the chief of the Foreign Affairs 
Department deplored the fact that China has not yet ratified the 
two 1966 conventions on human rights, which amend the 1948 
Universal Declaration of Human Rights. For his part, Mr. Qiao 
said the human rights situation had to be considered in light of 
China's development. 
<H5>  Reintegration in GATT </H5>
  The Chinese official's conversation with Otto Stich focused 
on Beijing's wish to rejoin the GATT, Federal Department of 
Finances spokesman Mario Carrera said. The Confederation 
president assured Qiao of Swiss support whenever China 
officially requests reintegration, once its commercial system 
has been modernized. Mr. Stich and Qiao also agreed that 
China's growth should keep pace with the development of social 
well-being. 
  Aside from the human rights question, Gret Haller, president 
of the National Council, raised the environmental problem, which 
often is neglected when a country such as China undergoes 
important economic and industrial changes. Qiao mentioned 
several laws that have been adopted in this field, but admitted 
that there sometimes is large distance between theory and 
practice. 
<H5>  Dalai Lama "Welcome" </H5>
  During his conversations, Qiao Shi called attention to Tibet 
and to the fact that the Dalai Lama would be welcome there for 
talks with the Chinese Government. The only thing "out of the 
question" would be independence. He also pointed out that the 
rights of minorities are written in the Chinese Constitution, 
and that freedom of worship also is guaranteed. However, up to 
a certain limit: The third most important Chinese explained that 
his country would accept no religious extremism whatsoever. 
[passage omitted] 
<H5>  Challenged Visit </H5>
  The Chinese official's visit to Switzerland already has 
caused protests. Some 30 Tibetans loudly protested his presence 
outside the Federal Palace, which was under the protection of 
grenadeers and dogs. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

