<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diplomat Announces New Trade Campaign To Target Japan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2601100594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0827 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2601100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 26 KYODO -- Britain will promote its 
trade with Japan in a new campaign starting April, David Warren, 
commercial counselor at the British Embassy in Japan said 
Wednesday [26 January]. 
  The campaign, named Action Japan, will focus on trade with 
Japan in nine specific industrial areas, Warren told a press 
conference at the embassy. 
  The areas are auto parts, electronic devices, construction, 
health care, fashion, textiles, food, environmental and marine 
equipment and projects in third world countries, Warren said. 
  Warren said British exporters should increase their efforts 
to successfully enter Japanese markets, which he termed 
"strategically the most important" for British firms operating 
in Asia. 
  He said he does not observe "significantly big institutional 
problems" in Japan that may hamper the smooth entry of British 
firms. 
  The campaign will replace the Priority Japan Program that 
began in 1991 and will expire in March this year, which called 
for raising annual British exports to Japan to 5 billion pounds 
(7.58 billion dollars). 
  Such exports totaled about 2.5 billion pounds in 1993, 
Warren 
said, noting more efforts are necessary both in governmental and 
private-sector levels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

