<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Sends UN Plans for Possible Bosnia Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2601173894 Paris AFP in English 1728 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2601173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Brussels, Jan 26 (AFP) -- The North Atlantic 
Treaty Organisation has sent the United Nations its plans for 
possible air strikes in Bosnia-Herzegovina and air support for 
UN troops there, a NATO spokesman said here Wednesday [26 
January]. He added that the 16-nation alliance was ready to 
meet any UN request to help break the siege of the Bosnian towns 
of Tuzla and Srebrenica. 
  Serb forces around Tuzla have prevented the re-opening of an 
airport there which is needed for UN aid operations. They have 
also hindered the relief of Canadian troops trapped at 
Srebrenica. 
  The spokesman said: "We have provided our plans for close 
air 
support (of UN troops under attack) and air strikes to the UN 
and we have offered to send a team to UNPROFOR (UN Protection 
Force) headquarters in Zagreb." 
  Speaking after a regular meeting of NATO ambassadors, he 
added: "We are ready to help the United Nations with its 
planning for the re-opening of Tuzla airport and the relief of 
the UNPROFOR contingent in Srebrenica." [passage omitted] 
  NATO sources said the UN's special representative in 
ex-Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi, would submit proposed plans for 
military intervention, including bombing, to the world body in 
New York on Friday. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

