<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EC's Brittan Urges Including Association Partners in EU </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2601184894 Paris AFP in English 1824 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2601184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Jan 26 (AFP) -- The integration of West 
and East Europe into a stable unit is the greatest challenge 
facing the European Community, EC Trade Commissioner Leon 
Brittan said Wednesday [26 January]. 
  In a speech delivered to businessmen in The Hague, he urged 
that countries bound to the EC with association agreements 
should be welcomed into the Community as full members. A text 
of the speech was distributed here. 
  Brittan said that the association agreements signed by the 
EC 
in 1992 with Hungary, Poland, the Czech and Slovak Republics, 
Romania and Bulgaria would create a free trade area stretching 
from the Atlantic Ocean to the Black Sea. 
  But he said it was crucial that the Community open its 
markets wider to East Europe and the countries of the former 
Soviet Union to promote economic progress, democracy and 
stability there. 
  "The future of the European Community itself depends on 
integrating (East European) countries into a prosperous and 
stable common future. It is as much in our interest as theirs," 
Brittan said. 
  Brittan also called on EC countries to retain faith in their 
target of a single currency, to work harder on aligning their 
economies, and to lower interest rates to promote economic 
recovery. 

</TEXT>

