<H3> <TI>   Italy Works For Release of Kuwaiti Prisoners in Iraq </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2001121394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1603 GMT 19 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2001121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "On Prisoners and Human Rights"] </F>
  [Text] Florence, 19 Jan (ANSA) -- Italy continues to work 
for the release of Kuwaitis still held prisoner in Iraq three 
years after the end of the Gulf War. 
  The commitment was reiterated today by Luigi Amaduzzi, 
diplomatic advisor to Italian Head of State Oscar Luigi 
Scalfaro, in a reply to a letter received on the occasion of the 
45th anniversary of the Human Rights Charter, from the president 
of the Italy-Kuwait Association, Pierandrea Vanni. The 
association's letter sought to bring to the attention of the 
head of state the problem of around 800 Kuwaiti prisoners still 
held illegally in Iraqi territory despite the fact the war in 
the area is over. 
  The Italian government has closely followed the evolution of 
this "tragic inheritance" of the Gulf War and has worked, in all 
opportune forums, to find a solution to the problem, according 
to Amaduzzi in his reply. He went on to say that Iraqi 
officials must understand the compelling need to respect basic 
human rights. 
  The Italy-Kuwait Association was formed in Florence two 
years 
ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-59113 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu018__a94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-018-A </AU>
