<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Urges Further Western Support for Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2601211694 Hamburg DPA in German 1947 GMT 26 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2601211694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speyer (DPA) -- Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel 
intends to assist the East European states with integration into 
the Western military alliance NATO. The federal government was 
also committed to creating concrete prospects for membership of 
the European Union, Kinkel said this evening in a speech before 
students at Speyer College of Administration. 
  The West had to support the democratic reforms in Russia to 
secure peace in Europe in the long-term, he said. However, the 
financial support given Russia had long ago reached the limits 
of the budget's capacity. The minister called upon the other 
Western industrial nations to provide greater financial support 
for Russia. 
  In Speyer, Kinkel once again spoke in favor of a permanent 
seat on the UN Security Council for Germany. The German 
Government wanted to play a part in deciding international 
problems that affected Germany. To that end, Germany would have 
to take part in UN military peace missions. It was important 
for the constitutional basis for Bundeswehr missions abroad to 
be established at last. 

</TEXT>

