<H3> <TI>   Economics Minister Urges GATT Air Traffic Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701123094 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1124 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Hamburg (DDP/ADN) -- Germany's Economic Affairs 
Minister Guenter Rexrodt today called for a multilateral GATT 
agreement on air traffic in Hamburg. Only regulated and fair 
competition can "prevent a new subsidy race," Rexrodt said 
during the handover to Lufthansa of a new Airbus model. 
Regarding recent complications involving the German-U.S. air 
traffic agreement, Rexrodt stated forcefully that "the United 
States also has to accept that its indirect support of air 
traffic is now open to question. Equality of opportunity in the 
skies has to apply worldwide." 
  Rexrodt backed the further expansion of air traffic in 
Germany. It is "extremely damaging" for Germany "that it is not 
possible to build a runway today without encountering 
resistance." Germany has to develop its airports if it wants to 
avoid being cut off from international traffic routes in the 
future. At the international level, Rexrodt called for fair 
"market entry opportunities" and a stop to "protectionism 
disguised as environmental protection." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

