<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Leaders Discuss Policy on Confidence Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2601180094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2601180094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Glavkos Kliridhis will send a letter to UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali outlining the positions of 
the Greek Cypriot side. Government spokesman Ioannis 
Kasoulidhis today said the letter is being prepared and must be 
sent by tomorrow. President Kliridhis informed the National 
Council of its content yesterday. 
  In light of developments, the political party leaders 
outlined their positions in statements to the Cyprus 
Broadcasting Corporation. 
  DISI [Democratic Rally] Chairman Ioannis Matsis said our 
side 
should turn toward discussing the substance of the Cyprus issue. 
He also said that the security issue should come at the 
beginning, which Rauf Denktas raised in his letter to the 
secretary general. Using the issue of security, Matsis said, we 
should turn toward international organizations and Europe and 
undertake initiatives and promote them at international 
decisionmaking centers. 
  AKEL [Restorative Party of the Working People] General 
Secretary Dhimitrios Khristofias said his party would be happy 
if in the end, our side's handling of policy results in 
disengagement from the discussion on the confidence-building 
measures with no political cost. Khristofias criticized our 
side, saying its handling of policy has led to many impasses and 
wasted time. Answering a question, he said he does not believe 
the secretary general will propose to return to a discussion of 
the substance of the Cyprus issue following the receipt of 
Kliridhis' letter. This, he said, should have been done a few 
months ago to achieve a specific result. 
  DIKO [Democratic Party] Chairman Spiros Kiprianou said that 
as things stand today, the only way out is to begin a dialogue 
on the substance of the Cyprus issue, putting forward issues 
relating to security and demilitarization. He also said he is 
optimistic for the long term on condition that we follow the 
correct policy and struggle in the right way. He added that 
this is subject to full cooperation with Athens. Kiprianou said 
that now is the time to hold a conference in Athens and added 
that he will raise the issue of a trip to Athens, even if it is 
only for the members of the National Council. 
  Socialist EDEK [United Democratic Union of Cyprus] Chairman 
Vasos Lissaridhis noted that with is stance since Kliridhis 
accepted the confidence-building measures and his recent letter 
suggesting that every measure be included in an overall 
discussion of the Cyprus issue, Denktas had offered a golden 
opportunity. Let us grasp what Denktas says and let us ask, 
finally, for a discussion of the substance of the Cyprus issue, 
Lissaridhis said. He added that he does not believe the 
secretary general or any country will say that our demand to 
discuss the substance of the Cyprus issue is illogical. 
  Konstandinos Themistokleous, vice president of the 
Democratic 
Socialist Renewal Movement [ADISOK], said our side should 
reaffirm its position that it accepts no regulation that would 
imply recognition of the pseudostate and will discuss all the 
other issues connected with the three documents [on the 
confidence-building measures]. Themistokleous said we cannot 
appear to be negative in our effort to discuss the 
confidence-building measures, because the United Nations 
considers that both sides now accept the measures in principle. 
He also said that the confidence-building measures are valid as 
a single package and cannot be implemented in stages. 
  Free Democrats Movement Chairman Yeoryios Vasiliou said the 
procedure being formulated now is dangerous. He said Turkey 
aims to maintain the status quo and if we enter a continuing 
dialogue on what Denktas does and does not mean, Turkey will be 
very happy. He said we cannot overcome the impasse by 
retreating or give the impression that we are retreating, 
because it will lead us into conflict with the United Nations 
and create a negative picture of our side for the world. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-59159 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu018_o_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-018 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

