<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton's Cyprus Report `Outdated,' `Out of Touch' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2701094694 Nicosia I MAKHI in Greek 27 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> NC2701094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia I MAKHI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Militant Comment" column: "The `Scrupulous' </F>
Package"] 
  [Text] U.S. President Bill Clinton described the package of 
confidence-building measures submitted by UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali as balanced and scrupulous and called on the 
two sides to accept it. We doubt whether the U.S. President has 
found time to deal with Butrus-Ghali's confidence-building 
measures. Some employees at the White House or State Department 
have again written the President's report, which appears to be 
three months late. Consequently, Clinton's report is outdated 
and out of touch with reality. Cypriot Hellenism demands that 
the U.S. President view the Cyprus issue seriously and honestly 
and stop acting as others have. He promised in Brussels that 
when he returned to Washington he would personally deal with the 
Cyprus issue. Instead of dealing with the substance and trying 
to promote an honest solution, he is signing documents presented 
to him by officials and submitting worthless reports written by 
bureaucrats. Robert Lamb, the U.S. State Department's special 
coordinator on the Cyprus issue, will come to Cyprus at the 
weekend but it appears that he will come to resuscitate the 
confidence-building measures. Unfortunately, the Americans do 
not appear willing to get seriously and effectively involved in 
the Cyprus issue and this disappoints Cypriot Hellenism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

