<H3> <TI>   Bosnian President Visits, Calls For NATO Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2701085494 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 0800 
GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2701085494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina President Alija Izetbegovic has 
declared that peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina can be achieved 
through a NATO air operation. 
  In a statement at Istanbul's Ataturk Airport, where he 
stopped over en route from Malaysia to his country, Izetbegovic 
said that the efforts of the UN Security Council and 
international organizations have so far failed to stop the 
Serbs. A NATO operation would bring peace, Izetbegovic 
reiterated, adding that the delay in such an operation has 
caused the deaths of 200,000 people and the occupation of 70 
percent of his country's territory. 
  In response to a question on the Turkish and Pakistani prime 
ministers' plans to go to Sarajevo, Izetbegovic said: Let them 
garner their courage and come. We are waiting for them. 
  Commenting on his visit to Malaysia, Izetbegovic explained 
that he was very pleased with his brief visit and received 
significant support from the Malaysian Government. 
  In his statement after seeing Izetbegovic off, Foreign 
Minister Hikmet Cetin said that the recent developments 
concerning Bosnia-Herzegovina were assessed. Cetin remarked 
that during the meeting with Izetbegovic, views were also 
exchanged on the conference on Bosnia-Herzegovina to be held in 
Geneva on 10 February. 

</TEXT>

