<F P=100> AUSTRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vranitzky, PRC's Qiao Shi Discuss Economy, Human Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701194294 Vienna ORF Television Network in German 1830 
GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2701194294 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna ORF Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Peter Fritz] </F>
  [Text] Qiao Shi, chairman of the PRC National People's 
Congress Standing Committee, was received by the president of 
the Austrian Parliament, by Foreign Minister Mock, and by 
Chancellor Vranitzky in Vienna today. Apart from economic 
issues, the talks also included the human rights situation in 
China. There was no change in the differing views held by the 
two sides. 
  Only a few people have demonstrated against the visit, 
calling for an end to Chinese rule over Tibet. 
  Qiao Shi was the head of the Beijing intelligence service 
for 
many years. Even during Qiao Shi's visit to Germany, critics 
said that his hosts would shake bloody hands -- an accusation 
which Chancellor Franz Vranitzky did not support: 
  [Begin Vranitzky recording] I think this formulation is 
inappropriate, and the point is not to shake bloody hands to 
make business, but, through reasonable cooperation, one day -- 
and, I hope, in the not too distant future -- we should achieve 
[a situation where] there will be no more bloody hands. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

