<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Economic Forum Session Opens in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kohl Urges G-7 Membership for Russia </H4>
<F P=102> AU2701200494 Paris AFP in English 1954 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Peter Mackler] </F>
  [Excerpt] Davos, Switzerland, Jan 27 (AFP) -- German 
Chancellor Helmut Kohl made a strong appeal Thursday [27 
January] for Western support of Russia's embattled reformers and 
backed permanent membership for Moscow in the Group of Seven 
industrial powers (G-7). 
  Speaking at the opening of the World Economic Forum here, 
Kohl sought to overcome Western misgivings about Moscow's new 
conservative cabinet and a feared drift away from its commitment 
to market reforms. 
  "The alternative is whether we give our support to those who 
support reform, not knowing whether they will succeed or not, or 
sit in our historical corner knowing the failure will be 
disastrous," he said. 
  Kohl said the possible expansion of the G-7 to give Russia 
permanent membership would be "a question of the greatest 
importance" at the group's July summit in Naples, Italy. 
  "They would not be just guests, they would be members of a 
round if this was provided by the democratic reforms in Russia," 
the German leader said in response to a question. "I don't see 
any alternative." 
  The G-7, which has agreed to provide Russia 43 billion 
dollars in assistance, comprises the United States, Japan, 
France, Britain, Canada, Germany and Italy. 
  In a keynote address to some 1,500 top political, business 
and media leaders gathered here, Kohl linked the West's future 
well-being to the success of economic and political reforms in 
the former Soviet bloc. 
  He urged active assistance for reform programmes throughout 
Central and East Europe and well stepped-up efforts to widen 
Western markets to imports from the East. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

