<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Economic Forum Session Opens in Davos </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bundesbank Chief Urges Deficit Reductions </H4>
<F P=102> AU2801094194 Paris AFP in English 0932 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2801094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Davos, Switzerland, Jan 28 (AFP) -- Monetary policy 
must not be used as a weapon against unemployment, Bundesbank 
president Hans Tietmeyer said here on Friday [28 January], while 
also condemning budget deficits. 
  Tietmeyer also called for a new relationship between growth 
and employment, and said that social support in Europe 
discouraged the creation of jobs. 
  Tietmeyer told the World Economic Forum here that his 
unequivocal message was that there should be no experiments in 
policies to combat inflation. Expansionist monetary policy 
could not be used to fight unemployment, he said. There was no 
alternative to rectification of structural causes of under 
employment. 
  He also warned against sliding budget deficits in Europe, 
holding that a stable monetary policy which left no room for 
inflation had to be linked to budgetary policies which did not 
lead later to an increase in taxation. 
  Tietmeyer posed the question of how to reduce the budget 
deficit without bearing down unduly on demand. The problem was 
how to do it at the appropriate time while being credible about 
the fact that the deficit would be reduced. 
  Growth was necessary in dealing with unemployment, but 
growth 
alone was not sufficient. A new relationship between growth and 
employment was needed. In European countries there were too 
many encouragements to be unemployed and these should be 
replaced by incitement to work. 
  He blamed rigidity in the labour market, a lack of 
flexibility in pay rates and a system of social welfare which 
discouraged the creation of jobs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

