<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Luxembourg's Santer on Banning Russia From CE </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701131494 Paris AFP in English 1301 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Strasbourg, Jan 27 (AFP) -- Russia should be barred 
from full membership of the Council of Europe [CE] for as long 
as it maintains troops in neighbouring countries without their 
accord, Luxembourg President Jacques Santer said Thursday [27 
January]. 
  Russia could not move closer to full membership as long as 
its foreign policy conflicted with international law, Santer 
told the winter session of the Council's parliamentary assembly. 
  "The stationing of troops in bordering countries, against 
their wishes, flies in the face of these principles," Santer 
added. 
  Russia did however have a "vocation" for full membership of 
the 32-nation organisation, Santer said. 
  Russia has since May 1992 sought to exchange its special 
"guest" status, which it has had for the past four years, for 
full council membership. 
  The head of the Russian delegation last Tuesday accused the 
Council of erecting "new, artificial obstacles" to full 
membership. 
  Russia fulfilled all the requirements for full membership 
after holding democratic elections and drawing up a new 
constitution in December, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-59192 </DOCNO>
