<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Official on Admission Schedule for New Members </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2701145794 Vienna DER STANDARD in German 27 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2701145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DER STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report signed "norb/tom/plo": "Accession Poker: Pressure </F>
on the European Parliament"] 
  [Text] Brussels/Vienna -- Commissioner Hans van den Broek, 
who is responsible for the foreign relations of the European 
Union, has suggested the European Parliament apply "expedited 
procedures" concerning the handling of the accession agreements 
with Austria, Sweden, Norway, and Finland. 
  Van den Broek proposed that only the "essential parts" of 
the 
agreements be submitted to the European Parliament by the end of 
March. 
  Thus, the European Parliament, which must ratify the 
expansion of the European Union, might begin preparations in 
March. Van den Broek no longer considers the presentation of 
complete treaties possible by 10 March. The president of the 
European Parliament, Egon Klepsch, believes that membership 
might be postponed by one year if negotiations are not concluded 
according to schedule. 
  Chancellor Vranitzky told DER STANDARD in Athens that 
contradictory statements by commissioners of the European Union 
or the European Parliament on the schedule are not surprising. 
It must be clear, however, that accession is a political 
decision that will be made ultimately at the government level. 
  Vice Chancellor Erhard Busek stated that, according to his 
information, there will be no delay in the talks. If problems 
should occur, it will still be possible to achieve a solution at 
the summit of the European Union in February. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

