<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Favors Openness in Military Expenses </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2801124994 Brussels BELGA in French 1411 GMT 27 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2801124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed GGD/LAR: "Mr. Delcroix Announces Greater </F>
Transparency in Military Purchases"; as released by Brussels 
BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Brussels, 27 Jan (BELGA) -- Defense Minister Mr. Leo 
Delcroix announced on Thursday [27 January] that he was seeking 
"greater transparency" in future purchases of military 
equipment, notably by involving Parliament in the decisionmaking. 
  "Initially, I am thinking of discussing files with the 
presidents and vice presidents of the Chamber and Senate 
national defense committees, which also include opposition 
members," he essentially affirmed during a press interview. 
  "It is a question of explaining a posteriori the reasons for 
deciding to purchase this or that equipment rather than other 
equipment," a close associate of the minister explained. 
  "If this initiative proves positive, Mr. Delcroix envisages 
further involving Parliament in discussions," he added. 
  "This must be a step in the right direction," added Mr. 
Delcroix, who denied that he was acting out of opportunism, a 
reference to certain military purchases -- including Agusta 
helicopters for the army -- which are the subject of a 
parliamentary committee of enquiry. 
  "But we must not go too far," added the minister, apparently 
excluding the setting up of a subcommittee charged with military 
purchases, similar to that which exists in the United States and 
the Netherlands. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

