<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Says UN Mission in Somalia `Gone Awry' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801124794 Hamburg DPA in German 1103 GMT 28 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD2801124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Bonn/Karlsruhe (DPA) -- According to German 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, the UN mission in Somalia has 
"gone awry." He admitted this at an FDP [Free Democratic Party] 
function in Karlsruhe yesterday evening. He emphasized, 
however, that 32 countries have attempted "to resolve this 
terrible situation." One thing has been achieved after all: 
"There is no more starvation there." 
  The Defense Ministry announced today that Chief of Staff 
Klaus Naumann will open a dam south of Beledweyne on Sunday [30 
January]. This is the last large project implemented with 
German humanitarian aid provided by the support unit in Somalia. 
[passage omitted] 
  The general will stay in Somalia until Tuesday. He is due to 
meet high-ranking UN officials in Mogadishu. [passage omitted] 
  Kinkel defended UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali 
against recent criticism. Ghali is an "immensely committed man, 
but far too much is asked of him." After the end of the 
East-West conflict, the United Nations is no longer in a 
position financially, organizationally, and regarding the 
available manpower, to handle all problems of the modern world, 
ranging from environmental to population problems. "We should 
not criticize Butrus-Ghali, but support him," Kinkel said. 

</TEXT>

