<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Steelmaking Division Causes Record Losses at Thyssen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2801123694 Hamburg DPA in German 0904 GMT 27 Jan 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2801123694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Duesseldorf (DPA) -- Large losses in its 
steelmaking division pushed the entire Thyssen group deep into 
the red last year. Thyssen AG announced today when presenting 
its annual accounts for the financial year, which ended on 30th 
September 1993, that its losses of 994 million German marks [DM] 
represented a new record in the company's history. 
  A year ago, the group, with its three divisions, steel, 
capital goods, and commerce, generated an annual surplus of 
DM348 million. Thyssen cut around 12,000 jobs in its domestic 
companies, and employed a worldwide workforce of 133,800 at the 
end of December. The steel and capital goods divisions were 
particularly affected by job losses. Staff cuts would continue 
in these sectors, Thyssen said. 
  The board of management described the results as "wholly 
unsatisfactory." The company added that its worldwide turnover 
during the 1992/93 financial year fell 6 percent to DM33.5 
billion. However, turnover during the first quarter of the 
1993/94 financial year rose again by 1.2 percent to DM8.1 
billion. Turnover shrank in the steel and capital goods 
divisions by 7 and 10 percent respectively. Economic results 
for the period October to December 1993 remained marked by high 
steel sector losses. The company is expecting largely negative 
results for the whole of this year, albeit with "continuous 
improvement each quarter." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

