<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets Ciampi, Urges G-7 Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2701162694 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1446 GMT 27 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2701162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Premier Chernomyrdin in Rome"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 27 Jan (ANSA) -- Economic reforms in Russia 
will continue with "firm determination," Italian Prime Minister 
Carlo Azeglio Ciampi told reporters after meeting Chernomyrdin. 
  The Russian premier, Ciampi said, is firmly convinced that 
reforms will move ahead and asked for Italy's support to be 
allowed to join the group of seven major industrialized nations. 
  Italy in July will host the G-7 summit in Naples and Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin is expected to attend the last day's 
session. 
  Chernomyrdin, Ciampi said, asked Italy to act so that the 
G-7 
may become the "G-8" beginning with the Naples summit. 
  As for reforms, Ciampi said he "heard with great pleasure a 
clear and full statement assuring that reforms not only will not 
move backward but will decisively move ahead." 
  According to Ciampi, it is "inevitable" that stabilization 
and renewal processes have their "ups and downs and alternating 
phases," but "the firm Russian determination is beyond question." 
  The G-7 summit, according to a joint statement released 
after 
the talks, will be "an important occasion" to make a progress 
report on Russian reforms towards a free market economy and for 
"a joint evaluation of international political events." 
  The statement speaks of Russian reforms as "fundamental" and 
also describes Russia as having an increasingly important role 
in "the construction of a new Europe." 
  The U.S.-sponsored Partnership for Peace, allowing Central 
and East European states closer ties with NATO, was also 
mentioned as a possible contribution to the creation of a single 
security system in the European continent, under the umbrella of 
the 52-member Organization for Security and Cooperation in 
Europe. 
  Chernomyrdin also spoke of the conflict in former 
Yugoslavia, 
saying that all efforts to stop the civil war there must be 
"peaceful and civil." 
  Ciampi and the Russian premier signed a political statement 
and a declaration of principles that will form the basis of a 
future investment cooperation accord, as well as a separate 
agreement on the burial of Italian soldiers killed during the 
Russian campaign of World War II. 
  Chernomyrdin on Friday will be received at the Vatican by 
Pope John Paul II and will meet Italian President Oscar Luigi 
Scalfaro. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

