<H3> <TI>   League To Break Government Program Accord With Pact </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2701130594 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2022 GMT 26 
Jan 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2701130594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "League Ready To Break With Pact"] </F>
  [Text] Rome, 26 Jan (ANSA) -- The Northern League on 
Wednesday [26 January] threatened to break a government program 
agreement made just two days ago with the Pact for Italy if Pact 
leader Mario Segni attempts to make an alliance with the former 
Christian Democrats, now called the People's Party [Italian 
Polular Party--PPI]. 
  "I will withdraw my signature because I don't want to make 
agreements with the People's Party," League official Roberto 
Maroni announced, adding that if Segni "ever thought that the 
League and the PPI could be together, he was fooling himself." 
  Maroni and Segni on Wednesday signed an accord that outlined 
a government program but fell short of an official alliance for 
the March 27 elections. 
  Segni today commented that the League was standing in the 
way 
of a broad anti-left alliance and, in apparent response to 
Segni, Maroni said that "we were with the Pact and were not 
three-way." 
  Maroni stressed the differences in political thinking 
between 
the People's Party and the program outlined in the agreement 
between League and Pact, especially the part calling for direct 
election of the prime minister. 

</TEXT>

