<H3> <TI>   Ciller Meets With Pakistan's Bhutto on Stopover </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2701183894 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1555 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2701183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, Jan 27 (AA) -- The prime ministers of 
Turkey and Pakistan on Thursday [27 January] agreed to continue 
their preparations for a planned visit to the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Prime Minister Tansu Ciller and her Pakistani counterpart 
Benazir Bhutto held a brief meeting on Thursday in Istanbul's 
Ataturk Airport, where the latter stopped over on her way to 
Davos, Switzerland where she will attend the World Economic 
Forum. 
  Ciller told reporters after her two separate meetings with 
Bhutto and Lebanese Premier Rafik Hariri, Turkey and Pakistan 
agreed that if the right circumstances are created preparations 
will continue for the Bosnia visit. 
  She added that both prime ministers are willing to go to the 
former Yugoslav republic, and the issue will be finalized in the 
coming days. 

</TEXT>

